The Expectation of the Minimum of IID Uniform Random Variables

Sep 25, 2016

In my STAT 210A class, we frequently have to deal with the minimum of a sequence of independent, identically distributed (IID) random variables. This happens because the minimum of IID variables tends to play a large role in sufficient statistics.

In this post, Ill briefly go over how to find the minimum of IID uniform random variables. Specifically, suppose that X1,,XnUnif(0,1)X1,,XnUnif(0,1) and let T=miniXiT=miniXi. How do we find E[T]E[T]? To compute this, observe that

P(miniXit)=1P(miniXit)=1P(X1t,,Xnt)=1i=1nP(Xit)=1i=1n[1P(Xit)]=1[1P(Xit)]n,P(miniXit)=1P(miniXit)=1P(X1t,,Xnt)=1i=1nP(Xit)=1i=1n[1P(Xit)]=1[1P(Xit)]n,

so the next step is to determine P(Xit)P(Xit). Due to the IID assumption, it doesnt matter which XiXi we use. Note also that to avoid adding cumbersome indicator functions, assume that t[0,1]t[0,1].

The value P(Xit)P(Xit) is easier to compute because it directly relates to the cumulative distribution function (CDF) of a uniform random variable. For Unif(0,1)Unif(0,1), the CDF is simply FX(x)=xFX(x)=x if x(0,1)x(0,1). This means

P(miniXit)=1[1P(Xit)]n=1[1t]n,P(miniXit)=1[1P(Xit)]n=1[1t]n,

so that by differentiating with respect to tt, the density function is fT(t)=n(1t)n1fT(t)=n(1t)n1 (the notation here with the TT as the subscript is to denote the variable whose density is being defined).

The reason why we need the density is because of the definition of the expectation:

E[T]=10tfT(t)dt=n10t(1t)n1dt.E[T]=01tfT(t)dt=n01t(1t)n1dt.

To compute this, we integrate by parts. Set u=t,du=dtu=t,du=dt and dv=(1t)n1dt,v=(1t)n/ndv=(1t)n1dt,v=(1t)n/n. We get

10t(1t)n1dt=(t(1t)nnt=1t=0)10(1t)nndt=[(1)(1(1))nn(0)(1(0))nn]+1n10(1t)ndt=1n[(1t)n+1n+1t=1t=0]=1n[(1(1))n+1n+1(1(0))n+1n+1]=1n1n+1.01t(1t)n1dt=(t(1t)nn|t=0t=1)01(1t)nndt=[(1)(1(1))nn(0)(1(0))nn]+1n01(1t)ndt=1n[(1t)n+1n+1|t=0t=1]=1n[(1(1))n+1n+1(1(0))n+1n+1]=1n1n+1.

Combining this with the extra nn factor we left out (you didnt forget that, did you?) we get E[T]=1n+1E[T]=1n+1. Notice that as nn the expected value of the minimum of these uniform random variables goes to zero. In addition, this expectation is always in (0,1/2](0,1/2] for n1n1. Thus, the answer passes the smell test and seems reasonable.
